<span id="xxi.ii.iv.vi-p65"></span> It is the doctrine of the \[medieval
and modern\] Church that Christ, as man, was perfect in knowledge from
the first, as if ignorance were hardly separable from sin, and were the
direct consequence or accompaniment of original sin. Cf. Aug. *de Pecc.
Mer.* ii. 48. As to the limits of Christ’s perfect knowledge as man,
Petavius observes, that we must consider ‘that the soul of Christ knew
all things that are or ever will be or ever have been, but not what are
only *in posse*, not in fact.’ *Incarn.* xi. 3, 6.

